\section{Homework 1}
\label{sec:org0204424}
Identify what you think the key story points are.
Did the authors do good job of highlighting that story?
How far along the flow from data to understanding did the paper go?
Could they have taken it further?

\subsection{Step 1}
\label{sec:orgee860d1}
\subsubsection{Necessary Conditions for Warm Inflow Toward the Filchner Ice Shelf, Weddell Sea (Daae et al. 2020)}
\label{sec:org7502032}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{What are the key story points?}
\begin{itemize}
\item Currently melt rates in the Filchner-Ronne ice shelf are low. What would conditions would need to be met for that to change?
\item To investigate a regional model is setup and the effects of three changes independently and combined are explored: (i) lifting of the thermocline (ii) fresher surface waters due to melt (iii) changes in surface stress.
\item They find that (i) and (ii) independently do little, but together they do a lot.
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Did the authors do good job of highlighting that story?}
\begin{itemize}
\item I think they did a very good job of highlighting the story. I enjoyed how they laid out exactly what they would do and then the results with little equivocating. It followed the scientific maxim of saying what you're going to do, doing what you said you'd do, and then saying what you did.
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{How far along the flow from data to understanding did the paper go?}
\begin{itemize}
\item I think it went very far. It clearly outlined what mechanisms are required to change conditions in the Filchner-Ronne. It didn't explain how/when those conditions would be met but that was out of scope of their study.
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Could they have taken it further?}
\begin{itemize}
\item I think it is a perfect length because it clearly and concisely answers the question it was interested in. Any further work would have required widening the scope of the study.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
