\subsection{Step 2}
\label{sec:orgbabaa96}
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org023c9c5}
In the Antarctic warm salty water which has the heat required to melt ice shelves from below lies underneath cold fresh water. Human caused climate change is warming this water and making it more shallow. Understanding how this warm water is able to access the grounding line of ice shelves is essential to predicting future melt. 
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org2db8455}
Can we estimate the mass loss of an ice shelf solely from the shape of its bathymetry and the depth of warm water at the shelf break?
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org1457403}
\begin{itemize}
\item We have introduced a metric called the GLIB which estimates the depth which warm water must reach to access the grounding line of an ice shelf.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:orge1686c5}

\subsection{Step 2}
\label{sec:org6b635ad}
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org7e89643}
In the Antarctic warm salty water which has the heat required to melt ice shelves from below lies underneath cold fresh water. Human caused climate change is warming this water and making it more shallow. Understanding how this warm water is able to access the grounding line of ice shelves is essential to predicting future melt. 
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org77ee4f1}
Can we estimate the mass loss of an ice shelf solely from the shape of its bathymetry and the depth of warm water at the shelf break?
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:org76f9032}
\begin{itemize}
\item We have introduced a metric called the GLIB which estimates the depth which warm water must reach to access the grounding line of an ice shelf.
\item We have shown with observations that ice shelves whose GLIB's lie beneath the depth of the warm water have significantly more ice shelf mass loss.
\item We have demonstrated the dynamics that drive the relationships we found in observations with numerically modelling.
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection{}
\label{sec:orgf5b069c}
In this work we have shown through observations and numerical modelling that the relationship between the depth of warm water off the shelf and the bathymetry of an ice shelf is the most important factor for ocean driven ice shelf melting. Using the relationship we have found between the ice shelf's bathymetry and ice shelf mass loss will allow us to make predictions of future melt.
